# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lit-element
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lit-element/components-overview] A Lit component is a reusable piece of UI.
[src:lit-element/components-overview] You can think of a Lit component as a container that has some state and that displays a UI based on its state.
[src:lit-element/components-overview] It can also react to user input, fire events—anything you'd expect a UI component to do.
[src:lit-element/components-overview] And a Lit component is an HTML element, so it has all of the standard element APIs.
[src:lit-element/components-overview] This example uses TypeScript decorators.
[src:lit-element/components-overview] See the Decorators documentation for more information on configuring TypeScript for decorators.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] The **Document Object Model** (**DOM**) is a cross-platform and language-independent API that treats an HTML or XML document as a tree structure wherein each node is an object representing a part of the document.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] The DOM represents a document with a logical tree.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Each branch of the tree ends in a node, and each node contains objects.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] DOM methods allow programmatic access to the tree; with them one can change the structure, style or content of a document.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Nodes can have event handlers (also known as event listeners) attached to them.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Once an event is triggered, the event handlers get executed.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] The principal standardization of the DOM was handled by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), which last developed a recommendation in 2004.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] WHATWG took over the development of the standard, publishing it as a living document.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] The W3C now publishes stable snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] JavaScript was released by Netscape Communications in 1995 within Netscape Navigator 2.0.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Netscape's competitor, Microsoft, released Internet Explorer 3.0 the following year with a reimplementation of JavaScript called JScript.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] JavaScript and JScript let web developers create web pages with client-side interactivity.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Legacy DOM was limited in the kinds of elements that could be accessed.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Form, link and image elements could be referenced with a hierarchical name that began with the root document object.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] A hierarchical name could make use of either the names or the sequential index of the traversed elements.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] For example, a form input element could be accessed as either `document.myForm.myInput` or `document.forms[0].elements[0]`.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] The Legacy DOM enabled client-side form validation and simple interface interactivity like creating tooltips.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] In 1997, Netscape and Microsoft released version 4.0 of Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer respectively, adding support for Dynamic HTML (DHTML) functionality enabling changes to a loaded HTML document.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] DHTML required extensions to the rudimentary document object that was available in the Legacy DOM implementations.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Although the Legacy DOM implementations were largely compatible since JScript was based on JavaScript, the DHTML DOM extensions were developed in parallel by each browser maker and remained incompatible.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] These versions of the DOM became known as the "Intermediate DOM".
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] After the standardization of ECMAScript, the W3C DOM Working Group began drafting a standard DOM specification.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] The completed specification, known as "DOM Level 1", became a W3C Recommendation in late 1998.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] By 2005, large parts of W3C DOM were well-supported by common ECMAScript-enabled browsers, including Internet Explorer 6 (from 2001), Opera, Safari and Gecko-based browsers (like Mozilla, Firefox, SeaMonkey and Camino).
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] The W3C DOM Working Group published its final recommendation and subsequently disbanded in 2004.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Development efforts migrated to the WHATWG, which continues to maintain a living standard.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] In 2009, the Web Applications group reorganized DOM activities at the W3C.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] In 2013, due to a lack of progress and the impending release of HTML5, the DOM Level 4 specification was reassigned to the HTML Working Group to expedite its completion.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Meanwhile, in 2015, the Web Applications group was disbanded and DOM stewardship passed to the Web Platform group.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Beginning with the publication of DOM Level 4 in 2015, the W3C creates new recommendations based on snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] To render a document such as a HTML page, most web browsers use an internal model similar to the DOM.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] The nodes of every document are organized in a tree structure, called the *DOM tree*, with the topmost node named as "Document object".
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] When an HTML page is rendered in browsers, the browser downloads the HTML into local memory and automatically parses it to display the page on screen.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] However, the DOM does not necessarily need to be represented as a tree, and some browsers have used other internal models.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] When a web page is loaded, the browser creates a Document Object Model of the page, which is an object oriented representation of an HTML document that acts as an interface between JavaScript and the document itself.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] A Document Object Model (DOM) tree is a hierarchical representation of an HTML or XML document.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] It consists of a root node, which is the document itself, and a series of child nodes that represent the elements, attributes, and text content of the document.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Each node in the tree has a parent node, except for the root node, and can have multiple child nodes.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Elements in an HTML or XML document are represented as nodes in the DOM tree.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Each element node has a tag name and attributes, and can contain other element nodes or text nodes as children.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Text content within an element is represented as a text node in the DOM tree.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Text nodes do not have attributes or child nodes and are therefore always leaf nodes in the tree.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] For example, the text content "My Website" in the title element and "Welcome" in the h1 element are both represented as text nodes.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Attributes of an element are represented as properties of the element node in the DOM tree.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] The DOM tree can be manipulated using JavaScript or other programming languages.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Common tasks include navigating the tree, adding, removing, and modifying nodes, and getting and setting the properties of nodes.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] The DOM API provides a set of methods and properties to perform these operations, such as `getElementById`, `createElement`, `appendChild`, and `innerHTML`.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Another way to create a DOM structure is using the innerHTML property to insert HTML code as a string, creating the elements and children in the process.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Another method is to use a JavaScript library or framework such as jQuery, AngularJS, React, Vue.js, Svelte, etc.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] These libraries provide an efficient way to create, manipulate and interact with the DOM.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] It is also possible to create a DOM structure from an XML or JSON data, using JavaScript methods to parse the data and create the nodes accordingly.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Creating a DOM structure does not necessarily mean that it will be displayed in the web page, it only exists in memory and should be appended to the document body or a specific container to be rendered.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] In summary, creating a DOM structure involves creating individual nodes and organizing them in a hierarchical structure using JavaScript or other programming languages, and it can be done using several methods depending on the use case and the developer's preference.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Because the DOM supports navigation in any direction (e.g., parent and previous sibling) and allows for arbitrary modifications, implementations typically buffer the document.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] However, a DOM need not originate in a serialized document at all, but can be created in place with the DOM API.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] And even before the idea of the DOM originated, there were implementations of equivalent structure with persistent disk representation and rapid access, for example DynaText's model disclosed in and various database approaches.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Web browsers rely on layout engines to parse HTML into a DOM.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Some layout engines, such as Trident/MSHTML, are associated primarily or exclusively with a particular browser, such as Internet Explorer.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] Others, including Blink, WebKit, and Gecko, are shared by a number of browsers, such as Google Chrome, Opera, Safari, and Firefox.
[src:lit-element/document-object-model] The different layout engines implement the DOM standards to varying degrees of compliance.
[src:lit-element/page] Lit is a simple library for building fast, lightweight web components.
[src:lit-element/page] At Lit's core is a boilerplate-killing component base class that provides reactive state, scoped styles, and a declarative template system that's tiny, fast and expressive.
[src:lit-element/page] You can build just about any kind of web UI with Lit!
[src:lit-element/page] The first thing to know about Lit is that **every Lit component is a standard web component**.
[src:lit-element/page] Web components have the superpower of interoperability: natively supported by browsers, web components can be used in any HTML environment, with any framework or none at all.
[src:lit-element/page] This makes Lit an ideal choice for developing **shareable components or design systems**.
[src:lit-element/page] Lit components can be used across multiple apps and sites, even if those apps and sites are built on a variety of front-end stacks.
[src:lit-element/page] Site developers using Lit components don’t need to write or even see any Lit code; they can just use the components the same way they do built-in HTML elements.
[src:lit-element/page] Lit is also perfect for **progressively enhancing basic HTML sites**.
[src:lit-element/page] Browsers will recognize Lit components in your markup and initialize them automatically–whether your site is handcrafted, managed via a CMS, built with a server-side framework, or generated by a tool like Jekyll or eleventy.
[src:lit-element/page] Of course, you can also build **highly interactive, feature-rich apps** out of Lit components, just as you would with a framework like React or Vue.
[src:lit-element/page] Lit’s capabilities and developer experience are comparable to these popular alternatives, but Lit minimizes lock-in, maximizes flexibility and promotes maintainability by embracing the browser’s native component model.
[src:lit-element/page] When you build an app with Lit, it’s easy to sprinkle in “vanilla” web components, or web components built with other libraries.
[src:lit-element/page] You can even update to a major new version of Lit–or migrate to another library–one component at a time, without disrupting product development.
[src:lit-element/page] If you’ve done any modern, component-based web development, you should feel right at home with Lit.
[src:lit-element/page] Even if you haven’t developed with components before, we think you’ll find Lit to be very approachable.
[src:lit-element/page] Each Lit component is a self-contained unit of UI, assembled from smaller building blocks: standard HTML elements and other web components.
[src:lit-element/page] In turn, each Lit component is itself a building block that can be used–within an HTML document, another web component, or a framework component–to build larger and more complex interfaces.
[src:lit-element/page] Lit doesn’t require compilation or building during development, so it can be used virtually tool-free if you prefer.
[src:lit-element/page] First-class IDE support (code-completion, linting, etc.) and tooling for production (localization, template minification, etc.) are readily available.
[src:lit-element/page] As we’ve already noted, Lit is a great choice for building all sorts of web UI, pairing the interop-based advantages of web components with a modern, ergonomic developer experience.
[src:lit-element/page] The team behind Lit has been involved with Web Components from day one.
[src:lit-element/page] We help Google maintain tens of thousands of components, offer a comprehensive set of web components polyfills, and engage deeply in standards and community work.
[src:lit-element/page] Every Lit feature is carefully designed with web platform evolution in mind; we aim to help you take full advantage of what the platform provides today while writing code that is ready to benefit from future enhancements.
[src:lit-element/templates-overview] If time permits, add new page on working with inputs, per outline.
[src:lit-element/templates-overview] Lit templates are written using JavaScript template literals tagged with the `html` tag.
[src:lit-element/templates-overview] The template syntax might look like you're just doing string interpolation.
[src:lit-element/templates-overview] But with tagged template literals, the browser passes the tag function an array of strings (the static portions of the template) and an array of expressions (the dynamic portions).
[src:lit-element/templates-overview] Lit uses this to build an efficient representation of your template, so it can re-render only the parts of template that have changed.
[src:lit-element/templates-overview] You can also use Lit's templating library for standalone templating, outside of a Lit component.
[src:lit-element/templates-overview] For details, see Standalone lit-html templates.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] One of the key features of web components is the ability to create *custom elements*: that is, HTML elements whose behavior is defined by the web developer, that extend the set of elements available in the browser.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] This article introduces custom elements, and walks through some examples.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] A custom element is implemented as a class which extends `HTMLElement` (in the case of autonomous elements) or the interface you want to customize (in the case of customized built-in elements).
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] This class will not be called by you, but will be called by the browser.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Immediately after defining the class, you should register the custom element, so you can create instances of it using standard DOM practices, such as writing the element in HTML markup, calling `document.createElement()`, etc.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] In the class constructor, you can set up initial state and default values, register event listeners and perhaps create a shadow root.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] At this point, you should not inspect the element's attributes or children, or add new attributes or children.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] See Requirements for custom element constructors and reactions for the complete set of requirements.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Once your custom element is registered, the browser will call certain methods of your class when code in the page interacts with your custom element in certain ways.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] By providing an implementation of these methods, which the specification calls *lifecycle callbacks*, you can run code in response to these events.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The position of a custom element in the DOM can be manipulated just like any regular HTML element, but there are lifecycle side-effects to consider.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Each time a custom element is moved (via methods such as `Element.moveBefore()` or `Node.insertBefore()`), the `disconnectedCallback()` and `connectedCallback()` lifecycle callbacks are fired, because the element is disconnected from and reconnected to the DOM.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] However, since these callbacks are typically used to implement any required initialization or cleanup code to run at the start or end of the element's lifecycle, running them when the element is moved (rather than removed or inserted) may cause problems with its state.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] You might for example remove some stored data that the element still needs.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] If you want to preserve the element's state, you can do so by defining a `connectedMoveCallback()` lifecycle callback inside the element class, and then using the `Element.moveBefore()` method to move the element (instead of similar methods such as `Node.insertBefore()`).
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] This causes the `connectedMoveCallback()` to run instead of `connectedCallback()` and `disconnectedCallback()`.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] To make a custom element available in a page, call the `define()` method of `Window.customElements`.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] This must start with a lowercase letter, contain a hyphen, and satisfy certain other rules listed in the specification's definition of a valid name.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The custom element's constructor function.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Only included for customized built-in elements, this is an object containing a single property `extends`, which is a string naming the built-in element to extend.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Once you've defined and registered a custom element, you can use it in your code.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The examples above register custom elements on the global `CustomElementRegistry` accessed via `Window.customElements`.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] This means every custom element name you register must be globally unique across the entire page.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] As applications grow and begin combining components from multiple libraries, global name collisions can become a problem — if two libraries both try to define `<my-button>`, one of them will fail.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] One way to use a scoped registry is to pass it to `Element.attachShadow()` via the `customElementRegistry` option.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] You can also associate a scoped registry after the shadow root has been created by calling `initialize()`.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] For declarative shadow DOM, you can use the `shadowrootcustomelementregistry` attribute on a `<template>` element.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Like built-in elements, custom elements can use HTML attributes to configure the element's behavior.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] To use attributes effectively, an element has to be able to respond to changes in an attribute's value.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The `attributeChangedCallback()` callback is then called whenever an attribute whose name is listed in the element's `observedAttributes` property is added, modified, removed, or replaced.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Note that if the element's HTML declaration includes an observed attribute, then `attributeChangedCallback()` will be called after the attribute is initialized, when the element's declaration is parsed for the first time.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] For a complete example showing the use of `attributeChangedCallback()`, see Lifecycle callbacks in this page.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Built in HTML elements can have different *states*, such as "hover", "disabled", and "read only".
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Some of these states can be set as attributes using HTML or JavaScript, while others are internal, and cannot.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Whether external or internal, commonly these states have corresponding CSS pseudo-classes that can be used to select and style the element when it is in a particular state.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Autonomous custom elements (but not elements based on built-in elements) also allow you to define states and select against them using the `:state()` pseudo-class function.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The code below shows how this works using the example of an autonomous custom element that has an internal state `"collapsed"`.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The `collapsed` state is represented as a boolean property (with setter and getter methods) that is not visible outside of the element.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] To make this state selectable in CSS the custom element first calls `HTMLElement.attachInternals()` in its constructor in order to attach an `ElementInternals` object, which in turn provides access to a `CustomStateSet` through the `ElementInternals.states` property.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The setter for the (internal) collapsed state adds the *identifier* `hidden` to the `CustomStateSet` when the state is `true`, and removes it when the state is `false`.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The identifier is just a string: in this case we called it `hidden`, but we could have just as easily called it `collapsed`.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] We can use the identifier added to the custom element's `CustomStateSet` (`this._internals.states`) for matching the element's custom state.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] This is matched by passing the identifier to the `:state()` pseudo-class.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] For example, below we select on the `hidden` state being true (and hence the element's `collapsed` state) using the `:hidden` selector, and remove the border.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The `:state()` pseudo-class can also be used within the `:host()` pseudo-class function to match a custom state within a custom element's shadow DOM.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Additionally, the `:state()` pseudo-class can be used after the `::part()` pseudo-element to match the shadow parts of a custom element that is in a particular state.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] There are several live examples in `CustomStateSet` showing how this works.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] In the rest of this guide we'll look at a few example custom elements.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] You can find the source for all these examples, and more, in the web-components-examples repository, and you can see them all live at https://mdn.github.io/web-components-examples/.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] First, we'll look at an autonomous custom element.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The `<popup-info>` custom element takes an image icon and a text string as attributes, and embeds the icon into the page.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] When the icon is focused, it displays the text in a pop up information box to provide further in-context information.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] To begin with, the JavaScript file defines a class called `PopupInfo`, which extends the `HTMLElement` class.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The class definition contains the `constructor()` for the class, which always starts by calling `super()` so that the correct prototype chain is established.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Inside the method `connectedCallback()`, we define all the functionality the element will have when the element is connected to the DOM.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] In this case we attach a shadow root to the custom element, use some DOM manipulation to create the element's internal shadow DOM structure — which is then attached to the shadow root — and finally attach some CSS to the shadow root to style it.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] We don't do this work in the constructor because an element's attributes are unavailable until it is connected to the DOM.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] In the above example we apply styles to the shadow DOM using a `<style>` element, but you can reference an external stylesheet from a `<link>` element instead.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] In this example we'll modify the `<popup-info>` custom element to use an external stylesheet.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] It's just like the original `<popup-info>` example, except that we link to an external stylesheet using a `<link>` element, which we add to the shadow DOM.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Note that `<link>` elements do not block paint of the shadow root, so there may be a flash of unstyled content (FOUC) while the stylesheet loads.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Many modern browsers implement an optimization for `<style>` tags either cloned from a common node or that have identical text, to allow them to share a single backing stylesheet.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] With this optimization the performance of external and internal styles should be similar.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Now let's have a look at a customized built in element example.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] This example extends the built-in `<ul>` element to support expanding and collapsing the list items.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Note that this time we extend `HTMLUListElement`, rather than `HTMLElement`.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] This means that we get the default behavior of a list, and only have to implement our own customizations.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] As before, most of the code is in the `connectedCallback()` lifecycle callback.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] You use a `<ul>` element as normal, but specify the name of the custom element inside the `is` attribute.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] So far we've seen only one lifecycle callback in action: `connectedCallback()`.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] In the final example, `<custom-square>`, we'll see some of the others.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The `<custom-square>` autonomous custom element draws a square whose size and color are determined by two attributes, named `"size"` and `"color"`.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The key function in this example is `updateStyle()` — this takes an element, gets its shadow root, finds its `<style>` element, and adds `width`, `height`, and `background-color` to the style.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The actual updates are all handled by the lifecycle callbacks.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] The `attributeChangedCallback()` callback is run whenever one of the element's attributes is changed in some way.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] As you can see from its parameters, it is possible to act on attributes individually, looking at their name, and old and new attribute values.
[src:lit-element/using-custom-elements] Note that to get the `attributeChangedCallback()` callback to fire when an attribute changes, you have to observe the attributes.
[src:lit-element/web-components] There are two parts to Custom Elements: autonomous custom elements and customized built-in elements.
[src:lit-element/web-components] Autonomous custom elements are HTML elements that are entirely separated from native HTML elements; they are essentially built from the bottom up using the Custom Elements API.
[src:lit-element/web-components] Customized built-in elements are elements that are built upon native HTML elements to reuse their functionality.
[src:lit-element/web-components] The Shadow DOM is a functionality that allows the web browser to render DOM elements without putting them into the main document DOM tree.
[src:lit-element/web-components] This creates a barrier between what the developer and the browser can reach; the developer cannot access the Shadow DOM in the same way they would with nested elements, while the browser can render and modify that code the same way it would with nested elements.
[src:lit-element/web-components] The impact of CSS scoped within the Shadow DOM of a particular element is that HTML elements can be encapsulated without the risk of CSS styles leaking and affecting elements that they were not supposed to affect.
[src:lit-element/web-components] Although these elements are encapsulated with regard to HTML and CSS, they can still fire events that can be picked up by other elements in the document.
[src:lit-element/web-components] The scoped subtree in an element is called a shadow tree.
[src:lit-element/web-components] The element the shadow tree is attached to is called a shadow host.
[src:lit-element/web-components] A Shadow DOM must always be connected to an existing element, either through attaching it as a literal element or through scripting.
[src:lit-element/web-components] In JavaScript, Shadow DOMs are attached to an element using `Element.attachShadow()`.
[src:lit-element/web-components] An HTML template defines a block of HTML content that is not rendered when the page loads, but can be instantiated during runtime.
[src:lit-element/web-components] Scripts within a template do not run, and resources are not fetched, until the content is cloned or added to the DOM.
[src:lit-element/web-components] Web Components are supported by current versions of all major browsers.
[src:lit-element/web-components] Backward compatibility with older browsers is implemented using JavaScript-based polyfills.
[src:lit-element/web-components] There are many libraries that are built on Web Components with the aim of increasing the level of abstraction when creating custom elements.
[src:lit-element/web-components] There are numerous community efforts for the Web Components ecosystem.
[src:lit-element/web-components] WebComponents.org provides an interface to search for any existing Web Components.
[src:lit-element/web-components] Custom Elements Everywhere validates whether popular front-end frameworks are compatible and ready to use Web Components standard, with a set of pending bugs and available workarounds.
[src:lit-element/web-components] Moreover, Vaadin Tutorials has a dedicated section that shows how those workarounds are used efficiently with example demo apps and similarly related topics.
[src:lit-element/web-components] In 2011, Web Components were introduced for the first time by Alex Russell at Fronteers Conference.
[src:lit-element/web-components] In 2013, Polymer, a library based on Web Components was released by Google.
[src:lit-element/web-components] Polymer is canonical implementation of Material Design for web application user interfaces.
[src:lit-element/web-components] In 2016, RequireJS was introduced as JavaScript library and AMD loader plugin for custom elements.
[src:lit-element/web-components] In 2017, Ionic (mobile app framework) team built StencilJS, a JavaScript compiler that generates Web Components.
[src:lit-element/web-components] In 2018, Angular 6 introduced Angular Elements that lets you package your Angular components as custom web elements, which are part of the web components set of web platform APIs.
[src:lit-element/web-components] In 2018, Firefox 63 enabled Web Components support by default and updated the developer tools to support them.
[src:lit-element/web-components] In 2018, LitElement was developed by the Google Chrome team as part of larger Polymer project.
[src:lit-element/web-components] LitElement was designed to be a lightweight and easy-to-use framework for creating web components.
